SIMPLE: morning
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Morning
<hw>Morn"ing</hw> <pr>(m⟦ocir⟧rn"⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>morning</ets>, <ets>morwening</ets>. See <er>Morn</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The first or early part of the day, variously
understood as the earliest hours of light, the time near sunrise; the
time from midnight to noon, from rising to noon, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The first or early part; <as>as, the
<ex>morning</ex> of life</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The goddess Aurora.</def> <mark>[Poetic]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morning</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Morning
<hw>Morn"ing</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Pertaining to the first part or
early part of the day; being in the early part of the day; <as>as,
<ex>morning</ex> dew; <ex>morning</ex> light; <ex>morning</ex>
service.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She looks as clear⟦br⟧
As <qex>morning</qex> roses newly washed with dew.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<cs><p><col><b>Morning gown</b></col>, <cd>a gown worn in the morning
before one is dressed for the day.</cd> -- <col><b>Morning
gun</b></col>, <cd>a gun fired at the first stroke of reveille at
military posts.</cd> -- <col><b>Morning sickness</b></col>
<fld>(Med.)</fld>, <cd>nausea and vomiting, usually occurring in the
morning; -- a common sign of pregnancy.</cd> -- <col><b>Morning
star</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>Any one of the planets (Venus, Jupiter,
Mars, or Saturn) when it precedes the sun in rising, esp. Venus. Cf.
<cref>Evening star</cref>, <er>Evening</er>.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd>
<cd>Satan. See <er>Lucifer</er>.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Since he miscalled the <qex>morning star</qex>,⟦br⟧
Nor man nor fiend hath fallen so far.</q> <rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <cd>A weapon consisting of a heavy ball set with spikes,
either attached to a staff or suspended from one by a chain.</cd> --
<col><b>Morning watch</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>the watch
between four <sc>a. m.</sc> and eight <sc>a. m.</sc>.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></cs>

<p><ent>Morning-glory</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Morning glory</ent>⟦br⟧
